<article data-history-node-id="7799" role="article" about="/content/plus-advent-calendar-2023" class="node node--type-package node--promoted node--view-mode-full">
  
    

      <footer class="node__meta">
      
      <div class="node__submitted">
        Submitted by <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span lang="" about="/content/users/mf344" typeof="schema:Person" property="schema:name" datatype="">Marianne</span></span>
 on <span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden">1  December,  2023</span>
        
      </div>
    </footer>
  
  <div class="node__content">
    
            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>In this year's advent calendar we revisit some of our favourite episodes of our <a href="/content/podcast" target="blank"><em>Maths on the move</em></a>  podcast. We're lucky to get to speak to lots of interesting mathematicians throughout the year, and our podcast captures many of those fascinating conversations, explores the maths people do, and why they love doing it. </p>

<p>Whether it's the maths of chocolate, new breakthroughs in pure mathematics, or the mathematical sound of music, we hope you enjoy this selection of <em>Maths on the move</em> episodes!</p>

